This listing is for a NEW OD Green Kel-Tec Sub 2000 G17 folding carbine, chambered in 9mm S&with a 16.1" barrel. It accepts all Glock Model 17 magazines, and comes with one mag. This gun is idea when you need the firepower of a long gun but need something light weight and very compact. It can be carried/concealed in just about anything and deployed instantly. Using readily available Glock 17 mags, this carbine makes for an ideal self-defense gun that can be taken just about anywhere with ease.

The SUB-2000 has a greatly extended range compared to a handgun. The superior precision is also very useful against small or partially covered targets at shorter range. The amount of training to master the SUB-2000 is only a fraction of that required for a handgun. This is an excellent choice for a vehicle gun, backpack gun, or anytime you might need something more than a handgun but do not have a lot of room and need something light and compact.

The bolt can be locked in the rear position by the operating handle. The main safety is of protected push bolt type disconnecting the trigger bar and interlocking the hammer and sear. By rotating the barrel upwards and back, the SUB 2000 can be reduced to a size of 16" x 7" to facilitate secure storage and utilize the internal deployment lock which is operated by a proprietary key. The rear sight is of aperture type and the fluorescent front sight can be adjusted for windage and elevation. The SUB-2000 can easily be disassembled without tools for cleaning or inspection.

title: For Sale:  UNFIRED: FABRIQUE NATIONALE / FN FNC 5.56mm Rifle
location: North STL County, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
Here's a real find! A previously owned but unfired, nearly new FN FNC semi-auto rifle.  Manufactured by FN Herstal of Belgium, the FNC (Fabrique Nationale Carbine) is a 5.56mm assault style rifle adopted by the armed forces of Belgian, Sweden, (as the AK5) and Indonesia.

The FNC is a sound design which accumulated best features from other famous designs, such as AK-47, and Colt/Armalite M16. The FNC operates with a gas piston very much like an AK except that the FNC has a gas setting for adverse conditions such as weak ammo or the gun being very dirty. The FNC also inherited features from the AR-15, like using the same magazines, making it a good, solid, all-around assault rifle. It's also the weapon that Al Pacino used in the bank heist scene in the movie "Heat".

Why Buy an FN FNC?
Besides being a remarkably rugged light rifle, the FNC also gives the owner an opening into the tremendously fun LEGAL machine gun hobby! 

In the world of fully automatic rifles here in the States, there is no question that the M16 reigns supreme. The downside is that an M16 these days on average will cost the buyer around $20,000 (which could put one heck of a dent in your mortgage). However, all hope is not lost for a buyer looking for a great 5.56mm rifle that you can rock and roll with at the range. This FN FNC is a great host for an entry level machine gun project that costs less than half of what you can buy an M16 for these days.

The approved, legal conversion is done via the installation of a BATF registered auto sear. One funny thing about the FNC sears is that there are in fact more registered auto sears in the USA than there are FNC Rifles! Anyways, you can buy this semi automatic FNC, and then buy a registered sear for about $3000, so for about $6500 you can have a legal "fun switch" on a great little rifle!

About this FN FNC:
Is the 18" Paratrooper version with the factory folding stock. Gun South Inc. of Birmingham Al import. Comes with (1) 30rd AR-15 magazine.
This particular rifle was purchased many years ago by a gun collector, who claims he never shot it. I am the 2nd owner. I’ve only field stripped it for inspection and oiling, and it looks factory clean. I have never shot it either. The rifle is in 97% condition, and while not appearing to be fired, was moved around quite a bit, with some handling marks, mostly on the top of the receiver. So blow up these pictures and look closely. Look above the "Nationale" and along the top. 

The price listed represents the cost for a highly collectible rifle, and a nice host for one of the registered auto-sears if you have the desire to own a fully automatic weapon.

title: For Sale:  Marlin 1894CP .357 Mag/38 Special 20 inch barrel
postcontent:
he original lever action Marlin Model 1894 was a typical Marlin lever action design for the time with a square bolt, solid top action, and color case finish on the receiver. Rifle, musket, and carbine versions of the Model 1894 were produced.

The Model 1894 was a short action chambered for the combination rifle/pistol cartridges of the day. By 1934 the demand for rifles shooting pistol cartridges had shrunk to the vanishing point, and the old Model 1894 was discontinued.

The advent of powerful magnum revolver cartridges, first the .357 Magnum and later the .44 Magnum, renewed interest in the concept, and the folks at Marlin realized that there was once again money to be made selling rifles for pistol cartridges. Rather than design a new action, they wisely put their excellent Model 1894 back into production. The new rifles came with blued rather than color cased actions and were made of superior modern steel, but otherwise were similar to the original Model 1894.

As I write these words in 2003, there are four variations of the standard Model 1894 centerfire rifles. These are the 1894PG (.44 Rem. Mag./.44 Spec.), 1894FG (.41 Rem. Mag.), 1894SS (.44 Rem. Mag/.44 Spec.), and 1894C (.357 Mag./.38 Spec.).

All of these standard Model 1894's are made with solid top receivers (drilled and tapped for scope mounts) and forged, machined steel parts. All come with genuine black walnut stocks that feature fluted combs, cut checkering and Marlin's Mar-Shield stock finish.

The Model 1894SS is similar to the 1894PG, but features a stainless steel barreled action and a straight grip stock. It is 37.5" long and weighs 6 pounds.

The 1894C is the carbine version, only available in .357 Magnum. It comes with blued steel metal parts, a straight grip stock, and an 18.5" barrel with a carbine type barrel band rather than a fore-end cap.

In addition to the standard Model 1894 rifles and carbines there are also special "Cowboy" variations. These are designed, no surprises here, primarily for the sport of cowboy action shooting. All Cowboy models come with tapered octagon, rather than round, barrels.

The standard Model 1894 Cowboy calibers are .45 Colt (24" barrel), .357 Mag./.38 Spec. (20" barrel), and .44 Mag./.44 Spec. (20" barrel). In the Magnum calibers and equipped with a low power scope these make perfectly adequate short range hunting rifles.

Perhaps the biggest advantage possessed by all of the Marlin 1894 lever action rifles is their solid top receivers, which allows a telescopic sight to be mounted low and overbore using a conventional one piece base on top of the receiver. Other desirable features of the 1894 rifles include fast repeat shot capability, ambidextrous operation, and the flat action without a bolt handle sticking out of the side makes them easy to carry.

The Marlin Model 1894 is a fine rifle, accurate and reliable. Its short action, designed for pistol cartridges form the beginning, makes it the best choice among the rifles so chambered today.

Note: Full length reviews of Marlin Model 1894 rifles in .357 Mag and .44 Mag. can be found on the Product Reviews page.

title: For Sale/Trade:  BEWARE
location: ALL OVER NORTH CAROLINA, Wilmington, North Carolina
postcontent:
Ok. So, I'm a very reasonable man. I sell guns on here, buy guns on here and trade guns on here. Any transaction that I have made has been done in accordance with the law and I assume that 99% of all the other users on this site do the same thing. 

HOWEVER, there are certain idiots on here that say that they are 18 years old, have pistol purchase permits and want to buy your gun. They will give you a list of reasons that they can buy a pistol and so on and so forth. The fact of the matter is, and you can ask a cop or look up the North Carolina General Statutes, anyone under the age of 21 (unless they are a cop) absolutely legally obtain a pistol purchase permit. It's basically impossible unless they do some very crafty forgery work. 

I guess what I'm saying is just be careful because there are a lot of idiots out there and legitimate buyers and sellers need to watch out for one another

title: For Sale/Trade:  .58 Cal Civil War Musket converted to Remington Rolling Block. VERY RARE
postcontent:
I received this rifle from the Great Grandson of a Civil War veteran who served with the Confederacy (I also got a signed letter from the Great Grand son to this effect along with his Great Grand fathers name so he may be located by Civil War historians). 

The story that has been passed down is that his Great Grandfather carried this actual gun in the Civil War and still bears the carvings of the Confederate Company he served in"A" Company, as well as a cross for his faith.From the patina of the metal, burn marks on the stock and the fact that every mark or stamp that was ever on this rifle is totally worn off attests to the fact that rifle served this family faithfully for a long time through very rough circumstances before it was retired to family heirloom status (Great Grandson.says he has shot it though).

Since the date for a standard Remington R.B. did not match the Civil War time frame exactly my initial thoughts were that this rifle was an early production Rolling Block but I later found that the 15 to 20,000 rolling blocks issued to Union troops during the Civil War time frame were of a split breech design which this rifle is not.

I was not ready to give up though because the previous owner was 110% sure this rifle was carried by his Great Grandfather in the Civil War so a local Remington collector, who was kind enough to assist with his considerable knowledge assisted and we explored the only other option which would explain this mystery. 

After the Civil War some soldiers who survived took their original .58 caliber muskets and had them professionally converted by Remington into the fast loading and desirable Remington Rolling Blocks. By doing it this way they still retained the muskets original .58 caliber barrel ,sights, forearm and stock! It also saved them money of course. So I was instructed to get bore measurements since this would be the only way to support the family claims all these years.

When I measured the breech it initially came out to .50 cal and my heart fell, BUT after my insistence that I believed the Great Grandson did not make this up the local collector asked me to look for a sleeve that Remington would have installed into the Civil War musket modifying it from the original .58 caliber down to the cartridge type .50-70 it currently is.

I looked and YES, there is a sleeve. I got out the digital calipers and the outside diameter of the sleeve on this rifle is in fact the .58 

In light of that information that would explain why the Great Grandfather was able to say this WAS the rifle he carried in the Civil War. While at that time it was not equipped with the Rolling Block mechanism everything else including his carvings of the stock identifying his company and the cross appear to be all correct making this a very rare rifle that saw duty in the Civil War and was professionally converted by Remington while still retaining the personalization and history of the Civil War soldier who carried it.

Even without this almost lost history a basic Remington Rolling Block is a valuable and heavy hitting rifle (were used later on as Buffalo Rifles and in many many battles and wars literally all over the world) and if you research our National Historic Firearms Museum in the United States the Remington Rolling block was the very first weapon to start what is now over 5000 classic firearms.

Upon his fathers death the previous gentleman inherited the rifle and his now deceased Pastor (prior to computers) who had an extensive weapons library researched the rifle for several weeks before getting back to him. Even at collector prices back then it was valued at between $800 and $1500. I have been told that this is obviously a low value number after so many years, but as they say it is worth what someone will pay for it and I will be reasonable to a serious collector.

The Great Grandson said they have fired this "cannon" and that it did very well but I have no .50 cal ammo and if I keep it I doubt I will ever fire it. I can tell you the action is very strong, tight and confident feeling and while the stock is a tad loose the rolling block mechanism operates as it was intended to over 130 years ago so if you were determined I am sure you could call it back into service once again or just admire it for the piece of American history it is.

That is where we currently are on researching the rifle until I visit another expert. I really have no interest for additional muskets trades at this time(thank you for the offers I have received on those) instead preferring some higher end modern weapons (or World War II weapons) or a reasonable cash offer.

Please read this. If you do have a reasonable trade send all of it's information along with pictures. If you have trouble sending pictures please send the written information on your trade and let me know you are having problems with sending things and we can figure that out.

Also since I am not an expert and I value any information or even corrections as I work towards getting this to a qualified collector who can display it properly and enjoy it for years to come.
